  "texts": [
    "While computing s test can be slow [several hours for a single test instance (Yeh et al., 2018; Guo et al., 2021; Hammoudeh & Lowd, 2022) ], it is still significantly faster than retraining O(n) mod- els.",
    "However, influence functions require that s test is recalculated for each test instance.",
    "Hence, when a large number of test instances need to be analyzed, retraining-based methods may actually be faster than influence functions through amortization of the retraining cost.",
    "In addition, while influence functions can be very accurate on convex and some shallow models, the assumption that Hessian H (T) is positive definite often does not hold for deep models (Basu et al., 2021).",
    "To ensure inverse (H (T)) -1 exists, Koh and Liang (2017) add a small dampening coefficient to the matrix's diagonal; this dampener is a user-specified hyperparameter that is problematic to tune, since there may not be a ground-truth reference."
